Wednesday, January 1, 1941

Went to the Stanford-Nebraska game with the family, George, Bobbi and Kathleen Arnold. A beautiful day and an exciting game. Drove too fast to check anything. Returned in the late evening. Many bad traffic snarls.

Page Edit History:

Thursday, January 2, 1941

People in to dinner tonight.

Friday, January 3, 1941

Drove to San Bernardino today to put Philip on his train. Started at 11 and got back at 6:20. Went up via the coast and Santa Ana Canyon; returned inland. Traveled too fast to check the road.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/30/2012 02:09 PM

  • BPOC 12/14/2010 01:30 PM

Saturday, January 4, 1941

Worked on income tax and other financial matters. Also herpetological odds and ends.
Saw Cy at the Zoo.
Shaw worked today.

Sunday, January 5, 1941

Spent the entire day segregating the Rhinocheilus specimens and preparing the borrowed ones for shipment. Had help from Chuck, a big job.

Wednesday, January 8, 1941

Stanley Mulaik called today on the phone (evening) but I was out at a movie.

Thursday, January 9, 1941

Went to Los Angeles on business on the morning train and returned on 2:15 stage. Mulaik called again-then left town so unfortunately I missed him.

Friday, January 10, 1941

Paul Breeze reports on ringed king found under trash in an orchard at Vista. Also a ring neck under a rock in an oat field, and 2 Pacifics in a crack in a large field rock in an oat field- Vista

Spent the entire day and evening in accounts-- annual statement and income tax.

Finished tabulating last years diary on Form 31C. Started in the annual census. Made good headway.

Saturday, January 1.8, 1941

Spent the morning on miscellaneous work including a visit to both NH Museum and the Zoo. All the rest of the day worked on the annual census. Shaw worked today. Breeze found 4 ring necks under rocks on a grassy hillside.

Saturday, February 8, 1941

Miscellaneous work all day, particularly lining up date to permit answers to correspondents. Tried to get into the dispersion papers and as usual had no luck.

Sunday, February 9, 1941

Finally gritted my teeth and got started on the dispersion paper today, after weeks of stalling. Made some progress, in fact surprised myself by finishing the first draft.

Saturday, February 15, 1941

Worked all day on the dispersion paper making many long calculations. Altogether made good progress- no wasted time.Chas Shaw worked today. Records from gander
1 Red Diamond med. brush & rocks Lakeside
1 Cal Boa L.

Sunday, February ^6, 1941

Continued on moment calculations, except when out to lunch. Made progress. The paper is nearly finished. Shaw worked again today.

Saturday, March 1, 1941

Spent the morning on miscellaneous items; also on reading the curve shape paper.

In the afternoon went to Palm Springs with gg Via coast to Olive; then through Santa Ana Canyon to Riverside and back to U.S. 60. It was rainy much of the way after many days of rain. Nothing seen.

Talked on reptiles at the Palm Springs museum. Stayed at Slavens.

Breeze reports large ruber in rock crack in brush 3 mi. E. of El Cajon.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/30/2012 02:21 PM
  • weinpal 03/26/2012 11:38 PM
  • weinpal 03/18/2012 11:20 PM
  • BPOC 12/14/2010 01:30 PM

Sunday, March 2, 1941

Returned from Palm Springs 10-2:30- still sainy. A tough trip. Nothing seen.

A little work on the curve paper in the evening.

Friday March 1, 1941

This evening at 5:30 drove to Buena Park where I put up at an auto-camp.

Page Edit History:
  • weinpal 03/26/2012 11:42 PM
  • weinpal 03/18/2012 11:23 PM
  • BPOC 12/14/2010 01:30 PM

Saturday, March 8, 1941

This morning at 9:30 picked up Chickering at the RR station in L.A.. A fine warm day. Then drove to El Centro where we arrived at about 5. Went via Redlands, Palm Springs, Travertine Rock and Westmoreland. Only one single lizard, Uta stans was seen all day. This was at Travertine Rock.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/30/2012 02:22 PM
  • weinpal 03/26/2012 11:47 PM
  • weinpal 03/18/2012 11:29 PM
  • BPOC 12/14/2010 01:30 PM

Sunday, March 9, 1941

Drove back to SD with Chickering. Started at 8 and arrived at 3, a fine warm day. Went via Benzone, Borego Valley, Yaqui Pass,Warners, Rincon and home. Only 2 lizards seen, both Uta stans. One was near Yaqui Well.

1 garter, med DOR Escondido grass 140 miles in the county.

Saturday, March 29, 1941

Went to see the flowers south of Bakersfield with gg and aunty allie. Started at 9:30. A cloudy day after a day of rain. The lupins were stupendous. Then returned to San Bernadino via Mojave, Palmdale and the Cajon Pass.

No reptiles were seen. 53 miles in the county. Total miles 388.

Shaw reports a Sonora occipitalis coming out of a hole at 5:30 PM. Bright sun shining. Clark Valley.

Sunday, March 30, 1941

Returned home via Palm Springs, Kane Springs and Julian. Stopped to visit Stillman Berry in Redlands and had a most interesting time. One dip was seen near Cathedral City. Picked up a red racer 5 mi. N. of Truckhaven DOR desert. Saw at least 2 snakes on the road in S.D. Co, one maybe alive but couldn't stop because of heavy traffic. Miles today 240.

Saturday, April 12, 1941

Went over to the Natural History Museum and the Zoo. Talked to Mrs. Benchley about papers. Got permission to start a new series under the title "Applications of Statistical Methods to Herpetological Problems".

Part 1 will be the frequency distribution and part 2 the desert vs coast.

David Mocine called.

Spent the rest of the morning checking some statistics in Grobman's paper.

Spent the afternoon and evening drawing random samples.

Notes:

Szlyna

Unsure of last name Grobman?

Friday, May 9, 1941

(Jim Deuel's trip of May 31)

In Kramer Hills shot several callys, one whiptail and a large 409 mom female leopard lizard. The latter continued the tail of a whiptail, the clytra of a large black beetle (not eleodes) and many vermilion colored berries in various stages of digestion. The lizard contained 12 (6+6) developing eggs. Had strong nuptial coloration.

1 Boyles King |COR| at Kramer Junct. Broad daylight, 5:17 P.M., 78 (410)
1 Desert Gopher |DOR| Kramer Junct. Kramer Junct., 7:40, 66
1 Sonora |DOR| 1 mi. S. of Kramer Junct. (411)

1 Sidewinder |COR| 3 mi. S. of Kramer Junct. 8:21, 65
1 Desert Gopher |DOR| 3 mi. E. of Kramer Junct.

Miles covered in evening drive 40, time 2 hrs.

Wednesday, May 14, 1941

(Shaw and Klamber May 31 Cont)

Found him at his house in Coolridge and talked shop for about half an hour. Then went to Tucson via Picacho Junct. Dodge says red and black racers are equally common at the monument headquarters. They cut Mexican Free-Tailed bats which live in the ruins.

1 Longnose |DOR| Randolph Typical lecontei short square blotches. Plenty red. Lt. brush of fields.
Bufo alvaruis |DOR| Randolph
1 Gopher L. |DOR| 7 mi. S. of Randolph fields
1 Dip |DOR| Redrock

Whip seen at Marana. Surprising how little DOR stuff there was along this road.

Arrived at Tucson at 4:30 Warm and part cloudy. Went to University and killed time catching insects. Couldn't find Shreve or Flock. Called on Arrington. He told us about various specimens which he promised to forward later. Went to San Xavier Mission at 7 P.M. There met Slevin and Wood and chewed the fat about collecting until 7:35.
Very interesting.

(May 15)

Notes:

Szlyna

Unsure about some of the spelling of the names, was a little hard to read.

Monday, May 19, 1941

Reptile club meeting last night. A poor meeting. Several mentioned finding rattlers up in brush. Bull frogs eat gold fish. Bobby M. says rattlers eat birds eggs.

1 Black Racer |DOR| 7 mi. E. of Apache Junction. A real piceus Black under throat. Light under rest of body+tail. Tail pink on top and light streaks carried forward on the body. Some light-eyed scales forward.

Saturday, May 31, 1941

This morning we started East from Mesa at 8:15. It was clear and warm but somewhat overcast later. Went ont via Apache Junction to Canyon Lake for chucks.
1 Snake skeleton 7 mi. N.E. from Apache Junct. but couldn't identify.

Caught the first chuck 1 mi. before reaching the Canyon Lake Bridge. Hunted all along from the first large rocks to the public camp ground about 1 mi. beyond the bridge. Altogether got 12 chucks. They were more numerous about 11:30 than when we were going in about 9. Uta O. Symmetrica, U.S. Stejnegeri and whiptails were also common.

Had lunch at Florence Junction and fixed specimens until 1:05. It was clear and warm.
Collected 2 dips 1 mi. S. of Florence Junct.

1 Patchnose S. |DOR| Apache Junct., Lt. brush.
Whip |SOR| 2 mi. S. of Florence JUnct.
Dip |SOR| 7 mi. N. of Florence
Bufo Alvaruis |DOR| Florence
1 Gopher L. |DOR| Florence, Creosate brush
1 Dip |DOR| 3 mi. W. of Florence.

Went to monument headquarters looking for Natt R. Dodge but he was out.

(Continued May 14)

Saturday, June 14, 1941

Shaw worked today. Spent the morning at UCLA checking a few specimens. Not much new. No new Rhinocheilus. Noted a worm snake No. 1571 from Riverside Mts., May 1, 1941. Collected by Bill Salt. Quite dark for Cahuilae. No Utahensis tendencies.

Saw Cowles and Vanderhorst. Went to President Sproul's for luncheon. Regents there.

Received honorary degree LLD in the afternoon.

Returned late in the evening.

Locality from R.M. Williams 8 mi. NW of Arbacle at Cortina Creek, Colusa Co. C. Marmorata.

The other recipients of LLD's were Harvey Seeley Mudd,the mining engineer, and Karl Compton. President of M.I.T.

Thursday, June 19, 1941

Attended the meeting of the Ich + Herp. poc in Pasadena today. Met many herps. There was a symposium on pit vipers in the morning and on Africa in the afternoon. Presided at the first and presented a paper on speciation in rattle snakes. Chap and I pulled out at about 5:20 reaching Banning at 7:12. Dusk but not dark. Clear and breezy. No moon.

1 Red Racer L |DOR| Owl, Light brush.

Monday, June 30, 1941

(July 4th Continued)

and started the evening drive earnest at 7:20. Worked hard until 1:30 MST with very indifferent luck. Never did a more thorough job with less success. The sky was overcast and cloudy with scattered showers and lightning in the mountains but we ran into only a few drops. The moon (a little more than 1/2 full) was obscured most of the time. There was a little breeze. It was quite hot, except up in the mesa toward Oracle Junction.

Left the mission at 7:20 and drove north to Ajo Junction. Still light.

1 H.T. (all P Solare) at the mission |COR| Ajo Junction at 7:35. Turned west down the Ajo road and went 4 miles.
1 H.T. at the Junction

Turned south again at Ajo Junction at 8:00.

1 Scute M |COR| 4 mi. S. of Ajo Junction 8:18 96 not quite dark.
1 Chilomeniscus small |COR| at the mission 8:23 96.

This was about 1/2 way between the mission and the corner. Turned at the mission at 8:25 and went north. No luck. turned into the Florence road at 8:55.

(Continued on June 29)

Wednesday, July 2, 1941

Morning. In for Los Angeles on business. Drove home in the afternoon. Slept part time so not to be counted.

(July 5 Continued)

Started again at 6:10. However it acted up over on the long lonesome road to Gila Bend and gave us a bad scare showing that the mechanic hadn't solved the problem. Fortunately it gave us no further trouble that night.

Cnemis 9 and 23 mi. W. of Gila Bend |SOR|
1 Arizona L |DOR| 10 mi. W. of Gila Bend. Field + Mesquite

Reached Gila Bend at 7:15. A great relief. Had supper and started on again at 8:00. After sun down and very warm. From here on we took temperatures frequently and found it from 100 to 105. Same in Mohawk + Gila Mts. No chance for snakes. 3/4 moon. 104 in Mohawks at 9:25. Quite dark. 105 in Gilas at 10:30. Drove slow. No use. Got a little cooler on the Yuma Plain.

1 Sidewinder M. |DOR| 11 mi. E. of Yuman Mesa Cor. saved head
1 Sidewinder M. |DOR| 8 mi. E. of Yuma Mesa Cor. 98
1 Gopher M |DOR| 5 mi. e. of Yuma Mesa Cor. saved. pure desert assn.

Reached Yuma at 11 P.M. MST. and Winterhaven at 10:10 PST. 116 here today but cooler now as it was whenever there was irrigation.

1 R. L. Lecontei |DOR| 1 mi. W. of Winterhaven
1 M.F. Frenatus L |DOR| 2 mi. W. of Winterhaven

Passed Casa Grande at 2:50. Got stuck for a short time 2 mi. W. and then got stuck for good 15 mi. W. a couple of good mining guys turned us around and towed us clear to Casa Grande. No charge. A mechanic who seemed to know his business said the carburetor was stuck. He overhauled it and we got

Tuesday, December 16, 1941

A M Jackley of South Dakota called this afternoon. Had a very interesting discussion with him particularly concerned with the rattler dens of South Dakota. He says they are 4 to 6 miles apart. Large males get there first. Easier to catch them in fall than spring. Many juveniles don't reach the dens; the ones which do follow the adults.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
